    <item>
      <title>Lucretius&#39; Dance of Atoms</title>
      <link>https://kohtaroyamakawa.github.io/posts/bookshelf/lucretius/</link>
      <pubDate>Sat, 25 Dec 2021 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://kohtaroyamakawa.github.io/posts/bookshelf/lucretius/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Lucretius was a Roman poet and philospher born in 94 BC.  He wrote a  six volume work called &lt;em&gt;De Rerum Natura&lt;/em&gt; or &lt;em&gt;On the nature of things&lt;/em&gt;, written in dactylic hexameter and known to detail the main tenants of Epicureanism.  It&amp;rsquo;s Book II has this passage in a section known as &amp;lsquo;The Dance of Atoms&amp;rsquo;.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;All bodies of matter are in motion. To understand this best,&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Remember that the atoms do not have a place to rest,&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
